nternal pudendal vein","Vertebral venous plexus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal iliac vein\u003C/strong\u003E is the main venous drainage conduit for the pelvic organs. It receives tributaries from the pelvic viscera (bladder, rectum, reproductive organs), gluteal region, and perineum before joining the \u003Cstrong\u003Eexternal iliac vein\u003C/strong\u003E to form the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon iliac vein\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal pudendal vein\u003C/strong\u003E is a tributary of the internal iliac vein and drains the perineal structures. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebral venous plexus\u003C/strong\u003E primarily drains the vertebral column and surrounding structures, not the pelvic organs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most pelvic veins drain into the internal iliac vein before joining the common iliac vein.","The internal iliac vein receives tributaries from the pelvic viscera, gluteal region, and perineum."],"references":["Sel\u00e7uk \u0130, Yassa M, Tatar \u0130, Huri E. Anatomic structure of the internal iliac artery and its educative dissection for peripartum and pelvic hemorrhage. Turk J Obstet Gynecol. 2018 Jun;15(2):126-129. doi: 10.4274/tjod.23245. Epub 2018 Jun 21. PMID: 29971190; PMCID: PMC6022419.","Arias DG, Marappa-Ganeshan R. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Arteries. [Updated 2023 Dec 9]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544319/","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53146"}},"questi